Kernel Heatmaps

Ernesto Carrella

June 27, 2016

Heatmaps

It seems like the future of human behaviour is all into drawing heatmaps. Right now the agents have very tiny memories: they just know where they have been last and how much money they made. Easy. However we’d like them to be able to infer that areas around “good spots” are probably also good. I think one way or another we’ve been discussing this for a very long time and I figured I should take a stab at it.

There are, I believe, many ways of doing inference geographically. However most methods are extremely heavy computationally (Kriging, Gaussian Processes), need a bit of work to adapt (Hidden Markov Chains) or might simply not work when the map is large (Gittins indices). I plan on trying to implement as many as possible of these, but for now we’ll try the simplest method which is Kernel regressions.

Drawing heatmaps

Kernel regressions are just a lofty name for predicting at a spot as a proportional average from all the other observations (where each weight is computed by a Kernel function).
I coded that in and made a video, down here. Whenever I click with my mouse I sample from the biomass distribution. On the right you see how the heatmap generated by the Kernel regression looks like. Initially it’s all 0. Then it’s equal to whatever I clicked the first time and then you can see it geographically separating. There are a couple of important parameters here that we could tune for years but I think this is a good first step.
